(40, 26, 27, 22, 5, 1, 1, 'Drink ye all of it', 'Connection of Drinking Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of drinking, with Matthew highlighting the communal aspect of drinking from the cup and Song of Solomon inviting friends to drink abundantly. This connection highlights the significance of shared experiences and intimacy in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 27, 22, 7, 9, 9, 'Drink ye all of it', 'Connection of Wine Imagery', 'This connection highlights the theme of wine as a symbol of sweetness and joy in both passages. In Matthew, the act of drinking from the cup signifies communion, while in Song of Solomon, wine is described as sweet and pleasing, evoking intimacy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 27, 23, 55, 1, 1, 'Drink ye all of it', 'Invitation to Drink', 'This connection highlights the theme of invitation to drink, as both passages emphasize coming to partake in something life-giving. Matthew 26:27''s ''Drink ye all of it'' parallels Isaiah 55:1''s call to ''come ye to the waters.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
